5000|$|Initially, 17 {{species were}} {{described}} within the genus <b>Macrocystis.</b> In 1874, Hooker, following blade morphology, {{put them all}} under the same taxon, <b>Macrocystis</b> pyrifera. In modern times, {{the large number of}} species were re-classified based on the holdfast morphology, which distinguished three species (M. angustifolia, M. integrifolia, and M. pyrifera) and on blade morphology, which added a fourth species (M. laevis) in 1986. In 2009 and 2010, however, two studies that used both morphological and molecular assessments demonstrate that <b>Macrocystis</b> is monospecific (as M. pyrifera), which is currently accepted by the phycological community ...|$|E
